<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="45" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="6.[139,1160,728,905]" pageId="6" pageNumber="45">
This south European species was reported more than a century ago from Legnica in 
<collectingRegion country="Poland" name="Dolnoslaskie" pageId="6" pageNumber="45">Lower Silesia</collectingRegion>
(
<bibRefCitation author="LETZNER K." box="[224,370,758,782]" pageId="6" pageNumber="45" pagination="184 - 188" refId="ref8681" refString="LETZNER K. 1874. Nachtrage zu seinem Verzeichniss der Kafer Schlesiens. Jahres-Bericht der Schlesischen Gesellschaft fur vaterlandische Cultur 51: 184 - 188." type="journal article" year="1874">Letzner 1874</bibRefCitation>
) and Ojców in Kraków-Wieluń Upland (
<bibRefCitation author="EICHLER W." box="[808,951,758,782]" pageId="6" pageNumber="45" pagination="138 - 149" refId="ref7643" refString="EICHLER W. 1914. Przyczynek do tegopokrywych Ojcowa. Pamietnik Fizyograficzny 22: 138 - 149." type="journal article" year="1914">Eichler 1914</bibRefCitation>
), and recently from Upper 
<collectingRegion box="[218,289,789,813]" country="Poland" name="Slaskie" pageId="6" pageNumber="45">Silesia</collectingRegion>
(
<bibRefCitation author="KROLIK R." box="[307,446,789,813]" pageId="6" pageNumber="45" pagination="126" refId="ref8591" refString="KROLIK R. 2006: Confirmation of the occurrence of Clitostethus arcuatus (P. Rossi, 1794) (Coleoptera: Coccinellidae). Wiadomosci Entomologiczne 52: 126. [In Polish]" type="journal article" year="2006">Królik 2006</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="GREN C. &amp; SZOLTYS H. &amp; GRZYWOCZ J. &amp; KROLIK R." box="[461,651,789,813]" pageId="6" pageNumber="45" pagination="31 - 52" refId="ref7933" refString="GREN C., SZOLTYS H., GRZYWOCZ J. &amp; KROLIK R. 2013. Beetles (Coleoptera) of the Lower and Upper Silesia - the current state of knowledge and new faunistic data: ladybird beetles (Coccinellidae). Acta entomologica silesiana 21: 31 - 52. [In Polish with English abstract]" type="journal article" year="2013">Greń et al. 2013</bibRefCitation>
), Wielkopolska- Kujawy Lowland (
<bibRefCitation author="RUTA R. &amp; JALOSZYNSKI P. &amp; KONWERSKI S. &amp; MAJEWSKI T. &amp; BARLOZEK T." pageId="6" pageNumber="45" pagination="91 - 112" refId="ref9186" refString="RUTA R., JALOSZYNSKI P., KONWERSKI S., MAJEWSKI T. &amp; BARLOZEK T. 2009. Ladybird beetles (Coleoptera: Coccinellidae) of Poland. Part 1. New faunistic data. Wiadomosci Entomologiczne 28: 91 - 112. [In Polish with English abstract]." type="journal article" year="2009">Ruta et al. 2009</bibRefCitation>
), Pomeranian Lake District (
<bibRefCitation author="CERYNGIER P. &amp; ROMANOWSKI J. &amp; ROMANOWSKI M." box="[510,757,820,844]" pageId="6" pageNumber="45" pagination="41 - 58" refId="ref7465" refString="CERYNGIER P., ROMANOWSKI J. &amp; ROMANOWSKI M. 2016 b. Ladybird beetles (Coleoptera: Coccinellidae) of Cedynia Landscape Park. Wiadomosci Entomologiczne 35: 41 - 58. [In Polish with English abstract]" type="journal article" year="2016">Ceryngier et al. 2016b</bibRefCitation>
) and Mazovian Lowland (
<bibRefCitation author="BODZON K. &amp; CERYNGIER P." pageId="6" pageNumber="45" pagination="115 - 129" refId="ref7071" refString="BODZON K. &amp; CERYNGIER P. 2016. Winter and early spring assemblages of ladybird beetles (Coleoptera: Coccinellidae) in two forest habitats in suburban area of Warsaw, central Poland. Studia Ecologiae et Bioethicae 14: 115 - 129." type="journal article" year="2016">Bodzon &amp; Ceryngier 2016</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="CERYNGIER P. &amp; ROMANOWSKI J. &amp; ROMANOWSKI M." box="[324,572,850,874]" pageId="6" pageNumber="45" pagination="177 - 186" refId="ref7506" refString="CERYNGIER P., ROMANOWSKI J. &amp; ROMANOWSKI M. 2016 c. Biedronkowate (Coleoptera: Coccinellidae) Parku Skaryszewskiego. In: J. ROMANOWSKI (ed.), Park Skaryszewski w Warszawie - przyroda i uzytkowanie, pp. 177 - 186. Wydawnictwo UKSW, Warszawa, 262 pp." type="book chapter" year="2016">Ceryngier et al. 2016c</bibRefCitation>
). Its current range expansion and increase in numbers can probably be attributed to climate change.
</paragraph>
